who command the Military Force3 and are subject to no one. This was, at Rome, to the Consuls 3 who, though they were in authority for a year only, were for the time the Rulers of Rome and the Roman world.

The whole texture of the paragraph shews not a trace of any authority granted to the subjects, of acting against Law, or judging of the safety of the People in opposition to the Prince. The Suprema Lex, superior to every actual Law, is put in the hands of him who has the Reyium Imperium and Militioe Jus Summum.

And that you may have the consent of the greatest writer in each language on this subJect, Aristotle says: “The Ruler, whether he be one or many, must judge on what subjects the Laws are incompetent to pronounce in particular, on account of the difficulty of including

every case in general expressions.’'
